/////////////////////////////////////////
What is Managed and umanged code interview questions


Great one üëç This is a very common C# interview question. Let‚Äôs break it down in simple words + interview style.


---

‚ö° Managed Code vs Unmanaged Code

üîπ Managed Code

Code that runs under the control of the .NET runtime (CLR).

CLR takes care of memory management, garbage collection, type safety, and security.

Example: Any C# or VB.NET code.


// Example of Managed Code
public class Test
{
    public void SayHello()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Hello, Managed World!");
    }
}


---

üîπ Unmanaged Code

Code that runs directly on the operating system (outside CLR).

You need to manually handle memory allocation and cleanup.

Example: C, C++, COM components, Win32 APIs.


// Example of Unmanaged Code (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    cout << "Hello, Unmanaged World!";
    return 0;
}


---

üéØ Interview-Friendly Answer

> ‚ÄúManaged code is the code that runs under the control of CLR in .NET, where memory management and garbage collection are automatic. Unmanaged code runs directly on the OS, like C or C++ code, where the developer must manually manage memory and resources.‚Äù




---

ü§î Possible Cross Questions

1. Can .NET work with unmanaged code?
‚úî Yes, using P/Invoke (Platform Invocation Services) and COM Interop.


2. Why is managed code safer?
‚úî Because CLR ensures type safety, garbage collection, and prevents memory leaks.


3. Can you give an example where you need unmanaged code in a .NET project?
‚úî For performance-critical operations or using existing C/C++ libraries (like image processing, hardware drivers).




---

üëâ Do you want me to also prepare a short diagram showing CLR in between managed and unmanaged code for quick revision?


