Perfect üëç Abhishek! Let‚Äôs break this into Definition + Project Use (Buy & Sell Properties App) + Trade-offs + Business Impact in very easy human words so you can speak smoothly in interview.





---



‚ùì Interview Question: What is the difference between const and static in C#? How do you use them in your project?





---



1. Definition (Easy Words)



const (Constant)

üëâ A value that never changes once the program is compiled.

It‚Äôs fixed, like a birthday ‚Äì can‚Äôt change once set.



static

üëâ A member that belongs to the class itself, not to objects.

It‚Äôs shared by all objects.

Like a common notice board in an office ‚Üí everyone can read/write, but there‚Äôs only one copy.







---



2. Project Use (Buy & Sell Properties App)



üí° In our Buy & Sell Property app:



Use of const



Example: Defining tax rate, max discount, or fixed strings.





public class PropertyConstants

{

    public const decimal MaxDiscountPercent = 10;

    public const string DefaultCurrency = "INR";

}



These don‚Äôt change at runtime, always fixed.





Use of static



Example: Logging service, cache, or utility class.





public static class Logger

{

    public static void Log(string message)

    {

        Console.WriteLine($"[LOG] {message}");

    }

}



All modules (Buyer, Seller, Admin) can use the same logger.









---



3. Trade-offs (Considerations)



Const



‚úÖ Very fast (replaced at compile time).



‚ùå If value changes later (like tax rate), you must recompile and redeploy.





Static



‚úÖ Saves memory (only one copy).



‚úÖ Good for global utilities (logger, cache).



‚ùå If misused, can cause state issues (shared data overwritten by multiple users).









---



4. Business Impact (Easy Words)



Using const ensures no accidental changes ‚Üí safe for business rules (e.g., max discount never exceeded).



Using static reduces memory usage ‚Üí faster and cheaper server resources.



But misuse of static (shared state) can cause bugs ‚Üí e.g., two users overwriting each other‚Äôs session if not handled properly.







---



‚úÖ Final Interview Line:

‚ÄúIn our Buy & Sell Property project, we used const for fixed rules like max discount and default currency, and static for utilities like logging and caching. Const gave us safety for business rules, and static reduced memory cost by sharing one copy across modules. The trade-off is that const values need redeploy if changed, and static must be carefully managed to avoid shared state issues.‚Äù





---



