////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////MSIL
üß† Definition (In Easiest Words)

MSIL stands for Microsoft Intermediate Language.
When you write C# code, it is not directly converted into machine code.
Instead, the C# compiler first converts your code into MSIL ‚Äî a middle language that any .NET platform can understand.

At runtime, the CLR (Common Language Runtime) converts MSIL into machine code (specific to your computer‚Äôs processor).

---

üîç Example

Suppose you wrote this code in C#:

int a = 10;
int b = 20;
int c = a + b;
Console.WriteLine(c);

When you compile this code:

1. It gets converted to MSIL instructions like:

ldloc.0
ldloc.1
add
call WriteLine

These are CPU-independent instructions.


2. Then CLR takes this MSIL and converts it into machine code that your PC understands.




---

üèóÔ∏è Project Use (Buy & Sell Properties App)

In your Buy & Sell Property Application, every time you build your project:

Your C# controllers, services, and models are compiled into MSIL.

When a user requests data (like viewing a property), CLR reads the MSIL, converts it to machine code, and executes it efficiently on the server.


So basically, MSIL makes your .NET app portable and fast ‚Äî it can run on any system where .NET runtime is available (Windows, Linux, macOS).


---

‚öñÔ∏è Trade-offs

‚úÖ Advantages

Platform independent (runs anywhere with .NET Runtime)

Improves performance through JIT (Just-In-Time) Compilation

Enables cross-language support (C#, VB.NET, F# etc. can work together)


‚ùå Disadvantages

Adds one extra compilation step (C# ‚Üí MSIL ‚Üí Machine Code)

First-time execution may be slightly slower due to JIT compilation



---

üíº Business Impact

Because of MSIL:

Your .NET application becomes cross-platform, reducing development cost.

The runtime automatically optimizes your code for the machine it runs on, giving better performance.

Developers don‚Äôt need to rewrite code for different operating systems ‚Äî saving time and money.


//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////I want to update the data by put request but that data is not available , what will happen ?

Scenario

You are sending a PUT request to update a record in the database ‚Äî
but the record (data) you are trying to update doesn‚Äôt exist.

Example:

PUT /api/users/10
{
  "name": "Abhishek",
  "email": "abhi@test.com"
}

But there is no user with ID = 10 in the database.


---

üß† What Happens

By default, a PUT request is expected to update an existing resource.

If the resource doesn‚Äôt exist, then there are two possible behaviors depending on your API design:



---

üÖ∞Ô∏è Case 1: Most Common (Safe) Behavior

‚úÖ The server will return an error ‚Äî usually HTTP 404 Not Found.
This means:

> ‚ÄúThe data you want to update doesn‚Äôt exist in the system.‚Äù



Example response:

{
  "status": 404,
  "message": "User not found."
}


---

üÖ±Ô∏è Case 2: Alternative Behavior (Upsert)

Some APIs are designed to create the record if it doesn‚Äôt exist ‚Äî
this is called ‚ÄúUpsert‚Äù (Update + Insert).

In that case:

The same PUT request will create a new record with ID = 10.

It will return 201 Created or 200 OK.


Example response:

{
  "status": 201,
  "message": "User created successfully."
}


---

üß© Summary (Easy to Remember)

Situation Result Status Code

Data exists Updated successfully 200 (OK)
Data doesn‚Äôt exist Usually error 404 (Not Found)
API supports Upsert Creates new data 201 (Created)



---

üèóÔ∏è Project Example (Buy & Sell Properties App)

In your app ‚Äî
If you send a PUT request to update a property that doesn‚Äôt exist:

PUT /api/properties/99

‚Üí Your API should return 404 Not Found,
so that the frontend can show:

> ‚ÄúProperty not found. Please check the ID or create a new one.‚Äù



////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Data Anotation in .net


> ‚ÄúData Annotations‚Äù are small labels (attributes) we put on our model properties to give extra meaning ‚Äî like saying ‚Äúthis field is required,‚Äù ‚Äúthis should look like an email,‚Äù or ‚Äúthis number can‚Äôt be more than 100.‚Äù



In short, they help validate data automatically before saving it to the database or processing it.


---

üß© Example (with simple explanation):

Let‚Äôs say we have a Property model in our Buy & Sell Property Application:

using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;

public class Property
{
    [Key]
    public int Id { get; set; }

    [Required(ErrorMessage = "Property Name is required")]
    [StringLength(100, ErrorMessage = "Property Name can't be longer than 100 characters")]
    public string Name { get; set; }

    [Range(100000, 100000000, ErrorMessage = "Price must be between 1 lakh and 10 crore")]
    public decimal Price { get; set; }

    [EmailAddress(ErrorMessage = "Please enter a valid email address")]
    public string OwnerEmail { get; set; }
}

üîç Explanation:

[Key] ‚Üí Marks Id as the Primary Key.

[Required] ‚Üí Makes sure Name cannot be empty.

[StringLength(100)] ‚Üí Limits the text length.

[Range()] ‚Üí Sets a price range.

[EmailAddress] ‚Üí Ensures a valid email format.



---

üß∞ How it works in the project (Project Use):

In the Buy & Sell Property App,

When a user adds a property through a form, these annotations automatically check if the entered data is valid.

If the name or price is missing, the API will return an error message before saving it to the database.

This helps maintain clean and reliable data.



---

‚öñÔ∏è Trade-Off:

Advantage Disadvantage

‚úÖ Less manual code ‚Äî validation happens automatically ‚ùå Only works for simple validation; for complex logic, you need custom validation attributes
‚úÖ Improves data consistency and security ‚ùå May not cover complex business rules directly



---

üíº Business Impact:

Fewer bugs and cleaner data ‚Üí users can‚Äôt submit wrong info.

Faster development ‚Üí less manual validation code.

Improves app reliability ‚Üí fewer crashes due to bad input.



---

üéØ **Interview Answer (Short & Impressive):

> ‚ÄúData Annotations in .NET Core are attributes we apply on model properties to perform validation automatically.
In my Buy & Sell Property App, I used them to validate property details like price, name, and owner email before saving.
It reduced code, improved data quality, and made the app more user-friendly.‚Äù


//////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////Condition Data Annotation
üß† Definition (Simple words like for a 5-year-old):
Conditional Data Annotation means ‚Äî
üëâ "You apply validation only when a specific condition is true."

For example:
üí¨ ‚ÄúIf IsMarried is true, then SpouseName should not be empty.‚Äù
Otherwise, no need to check it.

üíª Example (with explanation):
‚úÖ Step 1: Model class
using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;

public class Person
{
    public bool IsMarried { get; set; }

    [RequiredIf("IsMarried", true, ErrorMessage = "Spouse Name is required when married.")]
    public string? SpouseName { get; set; }
}
‚úÖ Step 2: Create custom attribute
using System;
using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations;
using System.Reflection;

public class RequiredIfAttribute : ValidationAttribute
{
    private readonly string _conditionProperty;
    private readonly object _expectedValue;

    public RequiredIfAttribute(string conditionProperty, object expectedValue)
    {
        _conditionProperty = conditionProperty;
        _expectedValue = expectedValue;
    }

    protected override ValidationResult IsValid(object value, ValidationContext context)
    {
        var property = context.ObjectType.GetProperty(_conditionProperty);
        if (property == null)
            return new ValidationResult($"Unknown property: {_conditionProperty}");

        var conditionValue = property.GetValue(context.ObjectInstance);

        if (conditionValue?.ToString() == _expectedValue.ToString())
        {
            if (value == null || string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(value.ToString()))
            {
                return new ValidationResult(ErrorMessage);
            }
        }

        return ValidationResult.Success!;
    }
}
üíº Project Use (Buy & Sell Property App)
In your Buy & Sell Property application,
you can use Conditional Data Annotation like this:

If IsForRent = true, then RentAmount must be required.
If IsForSale = true, then SellingPrice must be required.
Example:

public class Property
{
    public bool IsForRent { get; set; }

    [RequiredIf("IsForRent", true, ErrorMessage = "Rent amount is required when property is for rent.")]
    public decimal? RentAmount { get; set; }

    public bool IsForSale { get; set; }

    [RequiredIf("IsForSale", true, ErrorMessage = "Selling price is required when property is for sale.")]
    public decimal? SellingPrice { get; set; }
}
‚öñÔ∏è Trade-Off
‚úÖ Advantages	‚ö†Ô∏è Disadvantages
Keeps model clean and readable	Needs custom attribute logic
Automatically validates based on conditions	Might be harder to test if too many conditions
No extra code in controller	Performance overhead if used heavily
üí° Business Impact (Easy words):
Using conditional data annotations ensures users don‚Äôt miss required fields based on their selections.
üëâ This improves data accuracy, reduces form errors, and saves developer time in writing manual checks.

Would you like me to show the same validation working with Reactive Forms in Angular (frontend) for your Buy & Sell Property app?


